President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate two individuals to key positions in his Administration. 

The first nominee is Philip S. Goldberg, who is being nominated as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of the United States of America to the Republic of Colombia. Goldberg is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and has held various diplomatic roles, including serving as Chargé d’Affaires ad interim of the United States Embassy in Havana, Cuba, Ambassador to the Philippines, Ambassador to Bolivia, and Chief of Mission of the United States Office in Pristina, Kosovo. He has also served as Assistant Secretary of State (Intelligence and Research) and as the State Department’s Coordinator for the Implementation of United Nations Resolution 1874 on North Korea sanctions. Goldberg earned his B.S. degree from Boston University and is fluent in Spanish.

The second nominee is Jessica Lapenn, who is being nominated as the Representative of the United States of America to the African Union. Lapenn is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and currently serves as the Chargé d’Affaires at the United States Embassy in Pretoria, South Africa. She has held various diplomatic roles, including Deputy Chief of Mission of the United States Embassy in Kigali, Rwanda, and leading the Office for Human Rights and Humanitarian Affairs in the Bureau of International Organizations in Washington, D.C. Lapenn holds a B.A. from Harvard College and an M.Phil from Cambridge University.